-- Dr. Reddy's, Reliance, Jindal Steel, SpiceJet, IDBI: India Equity Preview
-- Thomas Kutty Abraham
-- 2010-06-14T02:47:49Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-14/dr-reddy-s-reliance-jindal-steel-and-spicejet-india-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
 unusual  price changes in India  trading . Stock symbols are in
parentheses and share prices are as of the  last close .  
 The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or  Sensex ,
gained 142.87, or 0.8 percent, to 17,064.95, the S&P CNX  Nifty 
Index on the National Stock Exchange rose 0.8 percent to
5,119.35 and the  BSE 200 Index  increased 0.5 percent to 2,166.32.
SGX CNX Nifty Index futures for June delivery added 0.4 to 5,135
at 10:38 a.m. in Singapore.  
 Indian banks: The government approved a 62.1 billion rupee
($1.3 billion) plan to bolster capital at five state-owned banks
to help them increase lending, the Finance Ministry said June 12.
 IDBI Bank Ltd.  (IDBI IN): will receive 31.2 billion rupees, the
 Central Bank of India  (CBOI IN) 20.2 billion rupees,  Bank of
Maharashtra  (BOMH IN) 5.9 billion rupees,  UCO Bank  (UCO IN) 3.75
billion rupees and  Union Bank of India  (UNBK IN) 1.11 billion
rupees, the ministry said in an e-mailed statement.  
 IDBI fell 0.5 percent to 112.3 rupees, Central Bank of
India retreated 1.6 percent to 146.15 rupees, Bank of
Maharashtra advanced 1.6 percent to 59.1 rupees, UCO Bank shed
0.3 percent to 81.2 rupees and Union Bank fell 0.6 percent to
306.95 rupees.  
 Dr. Reddy’s Laboratories Ltd.  (DRRD IN): The drugmaker
plans to appeal a preliminary injunction blocking its sales of a
generic copy of the allergy medication Allegra, the company said
in a statement to the Bombay Stock Exchange on June 12. The
injunction was granted by the U.S. District Court of New Jersey
at the request of Sanofi-Aventis SA and Albany Molecular
Research Inc. The stock retreated 2.1 percent to 1,466.05 rupees.  
 Hindustan Unilever Ltd.  (HUVR IN): India’s biggest
household-products maker said it will spend as much as 6.3
billion rupees buying back shares, its second such offer in
three years. The stock rose 0.3 percent to 252.75 rupees.  
 Jindal Steel & Power Ltd.  (JSP IN): The steelmaker
submitted a bid to buy 60 percent stake in Zimbabwe Iron and
Steel Co., the Economic Times reported on June 12, citing Ashish
Kumar, head of the company’s African business. The stock
advanced 2 percent to 641.95 rupees.  
 Reliance Communications Ltd.  (RCOM IN): Reliance Anil
Dhirubhai Ambani Group may sell a stake in its
telecommunications towers unit Reliance Infratel Ltd. before a
proposed sale of shares in Reliance Communications Ltd., the
Mint newspaper reported, without saying where it got the
information. Reliance Communications dropped 1 percent to 172.55
rupees.  
 Reliance Industries Ltd.  (RIL IN): India’s most valuable
company agreed to pay 48 billion rupees for control of Infotel
Broadband Services Ltd.  
 The Press Trust of India also reported Reliance may spend
as much as $5 billion to enter the telecommunications industry,
citing Chief Financial Officer  Alok Agarwal . Reliance plans
investments in power, telecommunications, financial services and
pharmaceuticals, the Economic Times reported, without saying
where it obtained the information. The stock rose 3.1 percent to
1,046.4 rupees.  
 Shree Renuka Sugars Ltd.  (SHRS IN): The biggest refiner
will buy 51 percent of Equipav SA Acucar & Alcool for 25 percent
less than it had agreed with the Brazilian sugar and ethanol
producer, the Economic Times reported, citing an unidentified
person close to the deal. Shree Renuka will pay about 11.5
billion rupees for the Brazilian company, less than the 15.3
billion rupees agreed to in February, it said. The shares fell
1.2 percent to 63.1 rupees.  
 SpiceJet Ltd.  (SJET IN): Kalanithi Maran, founder of
India’s SunTV Network Ltd., has bought a 37.7 percent stake in
discount carrier SpiceJet Ltd. for as much as 8 billion rupees,
the Economic Times reported yesterday. Maran paid between 45
rupees and 50 rupees per share to buy stakes from billionaire
Wilbur Ross and U.K.-based B.S. Kansagra, the newspaper reported,
citing an unidentified person close to the deal. He may offer to
buy an additional 20 percent of the carrier, the newspaper said.  
 SpiceJet plans to purchase at least 20 airplanes, doubling
its fleet, the Mint newspaper reported, without saying where it
got the information. The stock retreated 3.1 percent to 56.05
rupees.  
